The text for questions number 12 - 14

Indonesia has a lot of national parks to protect both the rare animals and plants.   One of them is Kerinci Seblat National Park. It is located in West Sumatra. We can find various animals in this park but it just has a few visitors. It may need some efforts to make people interested to visit this park.

The park shelters Sumatran elephants, tigers, clouded leopards, Malayan sun bears and tapirs, as well as hundreds of species of birds, and the world’s largest and tallest flowers. There are no orangutans, but occasionally sightings have been reported of the mysterious orang pendek, a bipedal ape similar to an orangutan, and the mythical sigau, half-lion and half-tiger.

The park is one of the Indonesia’s largest reserves. It covers an incredible 14,000 sq km (5,400 sq miles) of jungle and mountains. It is a home to the highest peak in West Sumatra, Gunung Kerinci. As the second highest volcano in Indonesia, Kerinci attracts climbers who are up for a serious challenge. The conservation centre has trained local guides to take the visitors for adventure on treks through the forest and climbing expeditions.

What is the writer’s intention of writing the text ?
A: To tell the history of Kerinci Seblat National Park.
B: To inform the recent condition of the Kerinci Seblat.
C: To promote Kerinci Seblat National Park in West Sumatra.
D: To give specific information about Kerinci Seblat National Park.

Soal: From the text we know that Kerinci Seblat National Park ….
A: covers 5,400 sq. kms of jungle and mountains
B: needs more promotion to attract more visitors
C: shelters hundreds of birds as well as orangutans
D: becomes a home of the highest volcano in Indonesia

Soal: The conservation centre has trained local guides … they can lead the visitors to hike.

The text for questions number 15 – 17

Washing your hands with soap is better, but if you have no soap and water, hand sanitizer is the second-best thing. Commercial hand sanitizer can get expensive so you can make your own sanitizer.

  • Here's what you'll need:
  • 2/3 cup 99% rubbing alcohol (isopropyl alcohol) or 190-proof grain alcohol (do not substitute other concentrations of alcohol)
  • 1/3 cup pure aloe Vera gel (preferably without additives)
  • 8 to 10 drops essential oil, such as lavender, clove, cinnamon, or peppermint
  • mixing bowl
  • spoon
  • funnel
  • plastic container
  1. Mix the alcohol and aloe Vera gel in the bowl. Pour the ingredients into the bowl and use the spoon to mix them together well. The mixture should be completely smooth. If you want the solution to be thicker, add another spoonful of aloe Vera. Or thin it out by adding another spoonful of alcohol.
  2. Add one drop of essential oil at a time. Stir as you go. After about 8 drops, smell the mixture to see whether you like the scent.
  3. Funnel the mixture into the container. Place the funnel over the mouth of the container and pour the hand sanitizer in. Fill it up and then screw on the lid until you're ready to use it.

What do we need to do after mixing the alcohol and aloe vera gel?
A: Add another spoonful of aloe vera carefully

Soal: What should we drop some essential oil for?

The text for questions number 18 - 20

Seahorses are tiny fish that are named for the shape of their head, which looks like the head of a tiny horse. There are at least 25 species of seahorses. Seahorses live in warm tropical waters all over the world. They prefer areas where they can find cover from predators. Coral reefs, seagrass beds, and places where rivers meet the sea are suitable for these defenseless creatures.

They are slow swimmers and therefore they are easy targets for predators. They often hang on to sea grasses with their tail to stay hidden. They swim upright among seaweed and other plants. Seahorses use their dorsal fins to propel slowly forward. To move up and down, seahorses adjust the volume of air in their swim bladders, which is an air pocket inside their bodies.

A female seahorse lays dozen, sometimes hundreds, of eggs in a pouch on the male seahorse’s abdomen. It is called as brood pouch as it resembles a kangaroo’s pouch. The babies hatch after 45 days in the brood pouch. They find other baby seahorses and float together in small groups, clinging to each other using their tails. Unlike kangaroos, baby seahorses do not return to the pouch. They must find food and hide from predators as soon as they are born.
